in the temperature.

00:56:54.420 --> 00:56:57.890
And the reheat temperature
of this model--

00:56:57.890 --> 00:56:59.640
Maybe I didn't describe
reheating exactly,

00:56:59.640 --> 00:57:01.910
I'll describe it
quickly in words.

00:57:01.910 --> 00:57:05.510
At the end of inflation,
the scalar field

00:57:05.510 --> 00:57:07.980
is destabilized by
these fluctuations

00:57:07.980 --> 00:57:12.060
and rolls down the hill, then
oscillates about the bottom.

00:57:12.060 --> 00:57:14.450
And when it oscillates
about the bottom,

00:57:14.450 --> 00:57:17.630
we need to take into account the
fact that this field interacts

00:57:17.630 --> 00:57:19.710
with other fields.

00:57:19.710 --> 00:57:22.590
And it then gives its energy
to the other fields, basically

00:57:22.590 --> 00:57:25.170
the standard model
fields ultimately,

00:57:25.170 --> 00:57:28.790
heating them up, producing
the hot soup of particles

00:57:28.790 --> 00:57:31.610
that we think of as the starting
point for the conventional Big

00:57:31.610 --> 00:57:33.000
Bang Theory.

00:57:33.000 --> 00:57:34.580
So this reheating
process at the end

00:57:34.580 --> 00:57:38.750
of inflation as
the inflaton field

00:57:38.750 --> 00:57:43.770
oscillates about its minimum,
reproduces the starting point

00:57:43.770 --> 00:57:46.587
of the conventional
Big Bang Theory.

00:57:46.587 --> 00:57:48.045
And it produces a
temperature which

00:57:48.045 --> 00:57:50.253
is comparable to the
temperature that you started at,

00:57:50.253 --> 00:57:53.040
which is the temperature
scale of the theory.

00:57:53.040 --> 00:57:55.410
So if it's Grand
Unified Theory scales,

00:57:55.410 --> 00:58:00.120
we would reheat to a temperature
of order 10 to the 16 GeV.

00:58:00.120 --> 00:58:02.570
And then, to ask what will
be the expansion factor

00:58:02.570 --> 00:58:08.370
between then and now, it would
be 10 to the 16 GeV times

00:58:08.370 --> 00:58:12.922
the Boltzmann constant
times 2.7 Kelvin.

00:58:12.922 --> 00:58:14.630
This is the ratio of
the temperature then

00:58:14.630 --> 00:58:18.716
to the temperature now,
both expressed as energies.

00:58:18.716 --> 00:58:20.340
And then we might
want to multiply this

00:58:20.340 --> 00:58:24.262
by 10 centimeters, if we say
that at the end of inflation,

00:58:24.262 --> 00:58:26.160
the universe was 10
centimeters across.

00:58:32.610 --> 00:58:34.003
Size at end of inflation.

00:58:43.330 --> 00:58:48.810
This, I worked out at
home, is about 450 times 10

00:58:48.810 --> 00:58:50.280
to the 9th light years.

00:58:55.700 --> 00:58:57.950
And we would want
something like 40 times 10

00:58:57.950 --> 00:59:01.406
to the 9th light years to
explain the present universe.

00:59:01.406 --> 00:59:03.820
So this is about
10 times too big.

00:59:03.820 --> 00:59:06.320
And that's OK.

00:59:06.320 --> 00:59:09.689
It means that we could
get by with one centimeter

00:59:09.689 --> 00:59:11.480
and 10 centimeters is
being a bit generous.

00:59:16.000 --> 00:59:18.240
So inflations would start
with this tiny patch.

00:59:18.240 --> 00:59:20.160
At the end of
inflation the patch

00:59:20.160 --> 00:59:23.150
would have grown
to one or maybe 10

00:59:23.150 --> 00:59:26.300
or perhaps more,
centimeters in length.

00:59:26.300 --> 00:59:28.820
And then by coasting
up to today it

00:59:28.820 --> 00:59:32.560
becomes something that's
larger than the region

00:59:32.560 --> 00:59:35.240
that we now observe.

00:59:35.240 --> 00:59:37.420
And that's basically
how the scenario works.

