00:59:52.270 --> 00:59:54.950
be where we'll stop,
although a few other things

00:59:54.950 --> 00:59:57.260
we might mention
if we have time,

00:59:57.260 --> 00:59:59.180
I want to talk about
how it solves the three

00:59:59.180 --> 01:00:01.805
cosmological problems
that we have discussed

01:00:01.805 --> 01:00:07.120
of the conventional
Big Bang model.

01:00:07.120 --> 01:00:10.750
And the explanations are
actually quite simple.

01:00:10.750 --> 01:00:13.890
So we can go through
them pretty quickly.

01:00:13.890 --> 01:00:20.410
First we had the horizons
slash homogeneity problem.

01:00:33.450 --> 01:00:38.300
Remember that was caused, or
could be stated as, the problem

01:00:38.300 --> 01:00:42.195
that the early universe
expanded so fast

01:00:42.195 --> 01:00:43.820
that the different
pieces of it did not

01:00:43.820 --> 01:00:45.710
have time to talk to each other.

01:00:45.710 --> 01:00:49.620
And, in particular, when the
cosmic microwave background was

01:00:49.620 --> 01:00:52.850
released, points at opposite
sides of the universe

01:00:52.850 --> 01:00:55.870
were separated from each other
by about maybe 50 horizon

01:00:55.870 --> 01:00:57.594
distances, we calculated.

01:00:57.594 --> 01:01:00.010
And that means there's no way
they could have communicated

01:01:00.010 --> 01:01:02.540
with each other, and
therefore no way we

01:01:02.540 --> 01:01:04.510
could explain how
they turned out

01:01:04.510 --> 01:01:07.930
to have the same temperature
at the same time.

01:01:07.930 --> 01:01:09.970
In this case, what
we've done is,

01:01:09.970 --> 01:01:12.350
we've inserted into the
history of the universe

01:01:12.350 --> 01:01:16.910
an extra phase of evolution,
the inflationary phase.

01:01:16.910 --> 01:01:18.510
And if we go back
to the beginning

01:01:18.510 --> 01:01:20.390
of the inflationary
phase, we see

01:01:20.390 --> 01:01:22.035
that that problem
is just not there.

01:01:22.035 --> 01:01:24.700
And if it's not there,
it doesn't develop later.

01:01:24.700 --> 01:01:26.890
At the beginning of
the inflationary phase,

01:01:26.890 --> 01:01:30.000
by assumption, the region that
we're starting to talk about

01:01:30.000 --> 01:01:32.570
was about horizon
length in size.

01:01:32.570 --> 01:01:35.990
And if we had enough inflation
to produce 10 centimeters out

01:01:35.990 --> 01:01:38.550
of that, that was 10
times more than we needed,

01:01:38.550 --> 01:01:40.990
it would mean that the entire
observed universe would

01:01:40.990 --> 01:01:42.910
be coming from a region
that would be only

01:01:42.910 --> 01:01:46.480
about a tenth of the size
of this Hubble length.

01:01:46.480 --> 01:01:50.290
So that would therefore
be well inside the horizon

01:01:50.290 --> 01:01:52.230
at that time.

01:01:52.230 --> 01:01:55.810
And that means that if you
allow a little bit of leeway

01:01:55.810 --> 01:01:59.130
with these numbers by having a
little bit of extra inflation,

01:01:59.130 --> 01:02:02.240
there can be plenty of time
for the entire region that's

01:02:02.240 --> 01:02:05.900
going to become our
personally observed region,

01:02:05.900 --> 01:02:09.250
to come to a uniform temperature
by the ordinary processes

01:02:09.250 --> 01:02:10.990
of thermal equilibrium.

01:02:10.990 --> 01:02:14.940
Because they're much less than
the horizon distance apart.

01:02:14.940 --> 01:02:18.410
And then once the uniformity is
established, before inflation,

01:02:18.410 --> 01:02:20.440
when the region that
we're talking about

01:02:20.440 --> 01:02:25.170
is incredibly tiny, inflation
takes over and stretches

01:02:25.170 --> 01:02:27.400
that tiny region
so that today, it's

01:02:27.400 --> 01:02:30.290
large enough to encompass
everything that we see.

01:02:30.290 --> 01:02:31.790
And therefore
everything that we see

01:02:31.790 --> 01:02:34.710
had a causally
connected past and had

01:02:34.710 --> 01:02:38.186
time at the early stages to come
to uniform temperature, which

01:02:38.186 --> 01:02:42.080
is then preserved as
the whole thing expands.

01:02:42.080 --> 01:02:46.240
So that gives a very
simple explanation

01:02:46.240 --> 01:02:49.830
for the homogeneity problem.

01:02:49.830 --> 01:03:04.190
Basically before inflation
the region was tiny.

01:03:09.430 --> 01:03:13.770
Second on our list was
the flatness problem.

01:03:20.970 --> 01:03:24.390
And the basis of that
problem was the calculation

01:03:24.390 --> 01:03:28.440
that we did about how omega
minus 1 evolves in time.

01:03:28.440 --> 01:03:29.950
And we discovered
that omega minus 1

01:03:29.950 --> 01:03:33.680
always grows in magnitude
during conventional evolution

01:03:33.680 --> 01:03:35.190
of the universe.

01:03:35.190 --> 01:03:41.560
And that therefore, for omega
minus 1 to be small today,

01:03:41.560 --> 01:03:44.885
it would have to be amazingly
small in the early universe,

01:03:44.885 --> 01:03:51.520
as small as 10 to the minus
18 at one second after the Big

01:03:51.520 --> 01:03:54.570
Bang to be consistent with
present measurements of omega

01:03:54.570 --> 01:03:55.330
minus 1.

01:03:58.570 --> 01:04:00.975
The key element there was
this unstable equilibrium

01:04:00.975 --> 01:04:04.230
and the fact omega L minus
1 always grew with time.

01:04:04.230 --> 01:04:06.440
And that depended on
the Friedman equations.

01:04:06.440 --> 01:04:09.350
During inflation, the
Friedman equations

01:04:09.350 --> 01:04:11.350
in some schematic sense
were the same equations,

01:04:11.350 --> 01:04:13.840
but the rows that go
into it are different.

01:04:13.840 --> 01:04:15.840
So the equations
basically are different.

01:04:15.840 --> 01:04:18.040
And if we look at the key
equation, the first order

01:04:18.040 --> 01:04:21.600
Friedman equation,
H squared equals

01:04:21.600 --> 01:04:29.764
8 pi over 3 G row minus
Kc squared over a squared.

01:04:29.764 --> 01:04:31.180
This was the
equation that we used

01:04:31.180 --> 01:04:34.932
to derive this flatness problem.

01:04:34.932 --> 01:04:36.390
We could see
immediately, if we now

01:04:36.390 --> 01:04:39.580
think about it, during
the inflationary process,

01:04:39.580 --> 01:04:41.750
things are completely reversed.

01:04:41.750 --> 01:04:45.670
Omega is driven towards
1, and exponentially fast.

01:04:45.670 --> 01:04:48.440
And the way I see that is to
just ask what is this equation

01:04:48.440 --> 01:04:50.260
do during inflation.

01:04:50.260 --> 01:04:52.120
And during inflation,
we just replace row

01:04:52.120 --> 01:04:54.640
by this constant
value row sub f,

01:04:54.640 --> 01:04:58.230
the energy density of the
false vacuum is fixed.

01:04:58.230 --> 01:05:01.510
And that means that during
inflation, this term is fixed.

01:05:01.510 --> 01:05:04.120
This term is falling off
like 1 over a squared.

01:05:04.120 --> 01:05:08.120
And a is growing
exponentially with time.

01:05:08.120 --> 01:05:12.020
So that means that
this term is decreasing

01:05:12.020 --> 01:05:16.720
relative to that term
by a huge factor,

01:05:16.720 --> 01:05:20.010
by the square of the
expansion factor.

01:05:20.010 --> 01:05:23.850
So in our sample
numbers over there,

01:05:23.850 --> 01:05:27.660
we were talking about an
overall expansion from 10

01:05:27.660 --> 01:05:31.110
to the minus 27
centimeters to 10.

01:05:31.110 --> 01:05:33.163
That's expansion by a
factor of 10 to the 28.

01:05:52.870 --> 01:05:54.910
In that case, during
inflation, this term

01:05:54.910 --> 01:05:58.350
decreases by a factor
of 10 to the 56

01:05:58.350 --> 01:06:01.190
while this term
remains constant.

01:06:01.190 --> 01:06:03.130
And that means that
by the end inflation,

01:06:03.130 --> 01:06:05.890
this is completely
negligible and this equation

01:06:05.890 --> 01:06:09.240
without this extra term means
you have a flat universe.

01:06:09.240 --> 01:06:11.140
So during inflation,
the universe

01:06:11.140 --> 01:06:15.450
is driven towards flatness,
like one over a squared, which

01:06:15.450 --> 01:06:18.360
is 1 over the square of this
exponential expansion factor,

01:06:18.360 --> 01:06:19.330
so very, very rapidly.

01:06:46.250 --> 01:06:49.410
And finally, the third of the
problems that we talked about

01:06:49.410 --> 01:06:50.555
was the monopole problem.

01:06:57.070 --> 01:07:01.230
We argued, originally
Kibble argued,

01:07:01.230 --> 01:07:03.890
that you'd expect approximately
one of these monopoles

01:07:03.890 --> 01:07:07.530
to form per horizon volume,
just because the monopoles are

01:07:07.530 --> 01:07:12.760
basically twists in
the scalar fields.

01:07:12.760 --> 01:07:15.760
And there's no way the scalar
fields can organize themselves

01:07:15.760 --> 01:07:18.360
on distances larger than
the horizon distance.

01:07:18.360 --> 01:07:20.146
So you'd expect
something on order

01:07:20.146 --> 01:07:21.270
of-- It's a crude argument.

01:07:21.270 --> 01:07:23.410
--but something on
the order of 1 not

01:07:23.410 --> 01:07:27.710
in the scalar field
per horizon volume.

01:07:27.710 --> 01:07:30.030
And that led to far too
many magnetic monopoles,

01:07:30.030 --> 01:07:32.880
fantastically too many.

01:07:32.880 --> 01:07:36.960
And the formation of one
monopole per horizon volume

01:07:36.960 --> 01:07:38.840
is hard to avoid.

01:07:38.840 --> 01:07:40.540
I don't know of any
way of avoiding it.

01:07:40.540 --> 01:07:42.980
But what gets us out
of the problem here,

01:07:42.980 --> 01:07:47.380
is that we can easily arrange
in our inflationary model

01:07:47.380 --> 01:07:49.640
for the bulk of the
inflation to happen

01:07:49.640 --> 01:07:51.726
after the monopoles form.

01:07:51.726 --> 01:07:53.100
And that means
the monopoles will

01:07:53.100 --> 01:07:57.230
be diluted by the
exponential expansion that

01:07:57.230 --> 01:08:00.260
will occur after
the monopoles form.

01:08:00.260 --> 01:08:01.850
The rest of the
matter is not diluted,

01:08:01.850 --> 01:08:03.400
because when
inflation takes place

01:08:03.400 --> 01:08:06.200
it's at a constant
energy density

01:08:06.200 --> 01:08:09.420
so the amount of other
stuff that will be produced

01:08:09.420 --> 01:08:12.840
is not diminished by
this extra expansion.

01:08:12.840 --> 01:08:14.940
But the monopolies,
which will produce first,

01:08:14.940 --> 01:08:18.000
will be thinned out
by the expansion.

01:08:18.000 --> 01:08:26.790
So the basic idea here
is that the volume goes

01:08:26.790 --> 01:08:34.760
by a factor of the order,
using our sample numbers,

01:08:34.760 --> 01:08:38.729
it's linearly growth by
a factor of 10 to the 28.

01:08:38.729 --> 01:08:41.680
Volumes go like cubes
of linear distances.

01:08:41.680 --> 01:08:45.160
So 10 to the 28 cubed is
10 to the 84, I think.

01:08:49.050 --> 01:08:49.905
Probably right.

01:08:53.609 --> 01:08:56.600
And that means that we
can dilute these monopoles

01:08:56.600 --> 01:08:59.840
by a fantastic factor and make
everything work, if we just

01:08:59.840 --> 01:09:01.569
arrange for the
monopoles to be produced

01:09:01.569 --> 01:09:03.661
before the exponential
expansion sets in.

01:09:07.439 --> 01:09:08.939
OK.

01:09:08.939 --> 01:09:11.420
Finally, and I think
this is probably

01:09:11.420 --> 01:09:16.762
the last thing we
will talk about,

01:09:16.762 --> 01:09:18.720
another problem that we
could have talked about

01:09:18.720 --> 01:09:20.029
and we'll talk about
the solution of it

01:09:20.029 --> 01:09:22.750
now, even though we never really
talked about as a problem,

01:09:22.750 --> 01:09:27.234
is the small scale
nonuniformities

01:09:27.234 --> 01:09:27.900
of the universe.

01:09:36.177 --> 01:09:37.760
And if we look out
around the universe

01:09:37.760 --> 01:09:39.609
we don't see a uniform
mass distribution,

01:09:39.609 --> 01:09:43.529
we see stars and stars collected
in galaxies and galaxies

01:09:43.529 --> 01:09:45.640
collected in clusters
and clusters collected

01:09:45.640 --> 01:09:49.819
in super clusters, a very
complicated array of structure

01:09:49.819 --> 01:09:51.410
in matter.

01:09:51.410 --> 01:09:53.290
Those are all nonuniformities.

01:09:53.290 --> 01:09:56.890
And we think we understand how
they evolve from early times

01:09:56.890 --> 01:09:59.880
because we also see in the
cosmic microwave background

01:09:59.880 --> 01:10:03.930
radiation, small fluctuations,
which we can now actually

01:10:03.930 --> 01:10:07.050
measure to very high
degree of accuracy.

01:10:07.050 --> 01:10:09.230
Those small fluctuations
provide the seeds

01:10:09.230 --> 01:10:12.350
for the structure in the
universe that happens later

01:10:12.350 --> 01:10:16.380
because of the fact that the
universe is gravitationally

01:10:16.380 --> 01:10:18.370
unstable.

01:10:18.370 --> 01:10:21.060
So at very early times
what we're seeing directly

01:10:21.060 --> 01:10:23.340
in the CMB, these
nonuniformities

01:10:23.340 --> 01:10:26.660
were only at the level
of one part in 100,000.

01:10:26.660 --> 01:10:28.950
But nonetheless,
in regions where

01:10:28.950 --> 01:10:30.510
there was slightly
more mass density,

01:10:30.510 --> 01:10:32.680
that pulls in
slightly more matter,

01:10:32.680 --> 01:10:34.940
producing still stronger
gravitational field

01:10:34.940 --> 01:10:38.590
pulling in more matter and that
amplifies the fluctuations.

01:10:38.590 --> 01:10:41.180
And that affect, we believe,
is enough to account

01:10:41.180 --> 01:10:44.000
for all the structure that
we see in the universe

01:10:44.000 --> 01:10:47.920
as originating from these tiny
ripples on the cosmic microwave

01:10:47.920 --> 01:10:49.004
background.

01:10:49.004 --> 01:10:50.420
But that still
leaves the question

01:10:50.420 --> 01:10:53.100
of where do these tiny
ripples come from.

01:10:53.100 --> 01:10:57.740
And in conventional
cosmology, one really

01:10:57.740 --> 01:10:59.810
had no idea where
they come from.

01:10:59.810 --> 01:11:03.220
One knew they had to be there
even before they were seen

01:11:03.220 --> 01:11:05.850
because we had to account for
the structure in the universe

01:11:05.850 --> 01:11:07.250
and how it evolved.

01:11:07.250 --> 01:11:10.021
When they finally were seen,
it was seen just right.

01:11:10.021 --> 01:11:11.020
Everything fit together.

01:11:13.950 --> 01:11:17.780
In inflationary cosmology,
the exponential expansion

01:11:17.780 --> 01:11:20.600
tends to smooth everything out.

01:11:20.600 --> 01:11:23.220
And for a while, those
of us working on it

01:11:23.220 --> 01:11:26.470
were very worried that inflation
would produce a perfectly

01:11:26.470 --> 01:11:28.980
smooth universe and we'd
have no way of accounting

01:11:28.980 --> 01:11:32.320
for the small fluctuations
that were needed to explain

01:11:32.320 --> 01:11:35.230
the existence of
stars and galaxies.

01:11:35.230 --> 01:11:38.340
But then it was realized
that quantum theory

01:11:38.340 --> 01:11:41.210
can come to our rescue.

01:11:41.210 --> 01:11:43.530
Classically, inflation
would smooth everything out

01:11:43.530 --> 01:11:46.560
and produce a uniform
mass density everywhere.

01:11:46.560 --> 01:11:49.310
But quantum
mechanically, because

01:11:49.310 --> 01:11:54.400
quantum mechanical theories are
fundamentally probabilistic,

01:11:54.400 --> 01:11:56.510
the classical prediction
of a uniform density

01:11:56.510 --> 01:11:59.920
turns into a quantum mechanical
prediction of an almost uniform

01:11:59.920 --> 01:12:03.240
density, but with some
places being slightly higher

01:12:03.240 --> 01:12:06.330
than that uniform density, other
places being slightly lower.

01:12:06.330 --> 01:12:07.960
And qualitatively,
that's exactly what

01:12:07.960 --> 01:12:11.396
we see in the cosmic microwave
background radiation.

01:12:11.396 --> 01:12:13.270
And furthermore, we can
do it quantitatively.

01:12:13.270 --> 01:12:15.790
One can actually
calculate the effects

01:12:15.790 --> 01:12:18.070
of these quantum fluctuations.

01:12:18.070 --> 01:12:19.990
And that's what I
want to show you now.

01:12:19.990 --> 01:12:22.690
The actual data on that,
which is just gorgeous.

01:12:25.330 --> 01:12:28.095
Shown here is the
Planck seven year data.

01:12:34.510 --> 01:12:37.410
Shown here is the
Planck seven year data,

01:12:37.410 --> 01:12:39.590
where what's being
plotted is the amplitude

01:12:39.590 --> 01:12:43.600
of the fluctuations versus
the angular wave length.

01:12:43.600 --> 01:12:46.070
One is seeing these as
a pattern on the sky.

01:12:46.070 --> 01:12:49.800
So the wavelength you see as
an angle, not as a distance.

01:12:49.800 --> 01:12:53.060
And long wave lengths
are at the left.

01:12:53.060 --> 01:12:54.940
Short waive lengths
are at the right.

01:12:54.940 --> 01:12:56.830
It's really done as
a multiple expansion,

01:12:56.830 --> 01:12:57.996
if you know what that means.

01:12:57.996 --> 01:13:00.700
And those numbers are
showing on the top.

01:13:00.700 --> 01:13:05.600
And the data points are
shown as these black bars

01:13:05.600 --> 01:13:07.980
with their appropriate errors.

01:13:07.980 --> 01:13:10.540
And the red line is the
theoretical prediction

01:13:10.540 --> 01:13:13.920
due to inflation, putting
in the amount of dark matter

01:13:13.920 --> 01:13:16.710
that we need to fit
the data that we also

01:13:16.710 --> 01:13:19.140
measure from the supernovae.

01:13:19.140 --> 01:13:20.712
And it's absolutely gorgeous.

01:13:20.712 --> 01:13:22.420
So I have a little
Eureka guy to show you

01:13:22.420 --> 01:13:25.240
how happy I was when
I saw this graph.

01:13:25.240 --> 01:13:27.960
And with the help
of Max Tegmark,

01:13:27.960 --> 01:13:31.040
we've also put on
this graph what

01:13:31.040 --> 01:13:34.830
other theories of
cosmology would give.

01:13:34.830 --> 01:13:36.950
So if we had an
open universe, where

01:13:36.950 --> 01:13:40.390
omega was just 0.2 or 0.3,
as many people believed

01:13:40.390 --> 01:13:45.080
before 1998, we would have
gotten this yellow line.

01:13:45.080 --> 01:13:47.720
If we had inflation
without dark energy,

01:13:47.720 --> 01:13:51.650
making omega equal what out of
matter, out of ordinary matter,

01:13:51.650 --> 01:13:53.650
we would get this
greenish line, which

01:13:53.650 --> 01:13:55.760
also doesn't fit
the data at all.

01:13:55.760 --> 01:13:57.760
And there's also something
called cosmic strings

01:13:57.760 --> 01:13:59.165
that we haven't talked about.

01:13:59.165 --> 01:14:01.890
It was for a time, thought
to be a possible source

01:14:01.890 --> 01:14:03.800
of the fluctuations
in the universe.

01:14:03.800 --> 01:14:08.447
But once this data came in, that
became completely ruled out.

01:14:08.447 --> 01:14:10.030
Now this is not quite
the latest data.

01:14:10.030 --> 01:14:12.820
The latest data come from
the Planck satellite.

01:14:12.820 --> 01:14:14.850
And it was released last March.

01:14:14.850 --> 01:14:17.890
And I don't have that
plotted on the same scale,

01:14:17.890 --> 01:14:20.010
but this is the latest
data which, as you see,

01:14:20.010 --> 01:14:24.209
fits even more gorgeously
than the data from WMAP.

01:14:24.209 --> 01:14:25.750
The more accurately
it gets measured,

01:14:25.750 --> 01:14:29.700
the better it fits the
theoretical expectations.

01:14:29.700 --> 01:14:32.120
Now I should mention for
truth in advertising,

01:14:32.120 --> 01:14:36.400
that this data is to some
extent fit to the model.

01:14:36.400 --> 01:14:40.590
It's actually a
six parameter fit.

01:14:40.590 --> 01:14:42.820
But of those six parameters,
I don't have time

01:14:42.820 --> 01:14:44.930
to talk about them in
detail, but four of them

01:14:44.930 --> 01:14:49.420
are pretty much determined
by other features.

01:14:49.420 --> 01:14:50.976
Two of them are just
fit to the data.

01:14:50.976 --> 01:14:52.350
And one of them
is something that

01:14:52.350 --> 01:14:55.030
changes the shape a little bit.

01:14:55.030 --> 01:14:57.900
It's the opacity of
the space between us

01:14:57.900 --> 01:15:00.440
and the surface of
last scattering.

01:15:00.440 --> 01:15:03.280
An important parameter that's
fit that you should know about,

01:15:03.280 --> 01:15:04.860
is the height of the curve.

01:15:04.860 --> 01:15:07.110
The height of the curve
can, in principle,

01:15:07.110 --> 01:15:09.240
be predicted by
inflation if you knew

01:15:09.240 --> 01:15:11.340
the full details of
this potential energy

01:15:11.340 --> 01:15:13.700
function that I've erased
for the scalar field.

01:15:13.700 --> 01:15:14.330
But we don't.

01:15:14.330 --> 01:15:15.930
We just have some
qualitative idea

01:15:15.930 --> 01:15:17.440
about what it might look like.

01:15:17.440 --> 01:15:19.990
So the height of the
curve is fit to the data.

01:15:19.990 --> 01:15:23.010
But nonetheless, the location of
all these peaks and everything

01:15:23.010 --> 01:15:25.640
really just come out of the
theory and it's just gorgeous.

01:15:25.640 --> 01:15:28.070
And it works wonderfully.

01:15:28.070 --> 01:15:30.410
So the bottom line
is I think inflation

01:15:30.410 --> 01:15:33.680
does look like a very good
explanation for the very

01:15:33.680 --> 01:15:34.830
early universe.

01:15:34.830 --> 01:15:37.750
It's kind of bizarre since
it talks about times like 10

01:15:37.750 --> 01:15:41.140
to the minus 35 seconds
after the Big Bang which

01:15:41.140 --> 01:15:45.310
seemed like a totally incredible
extrapolation from physics

01:15:45.310 --> 01:15:46.410
that we know.

01:15:46.410 --> 01:15:48.750
But nonetheless,
marvelously, it produces

01:15:48.750 --> 01:15:53.760
data that agrees fantastically
with what astronomers are now

01:15:53.760 --> 01:15:55.157
measuring.

01:15:55.157 --> 01:15:55.990
So we'll stop there.

01:15:55.990 --> 01:15:58.387
I want to thank you all
for being in the class.

01:15:58.387 --> 01:15:59.970
It's really been a
fun class to teach.

01:15:59.970 --> 01:16:02.990
I have very much enjoyed
all of your questions

01:16:02.990 --> 01:16:04.710
and enjoyed getting
to know you and hope

01:16:04.710 --> 01:16:06.630
to continue to see you around.

01:16:06.630 --> 01:16:08.330
Thank you.

